Recommendation/s:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant, in coordination with the Municipal Engineering Office (MEO) and the Municipal Planning and Development Office (MPDO), to:
a. Reclassify the identified completed projects amounting to P49,250,505.53 from the Construction in Progress (CIP) account to their appropriate Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE) classifications, and record the corresponding depreciation for each project from the date it became available for use, in accordance with Section 50 and Section 71 of the NGAS Manual and IPSAS;
b. Prepare the necessary working papers and Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) to support the reclassification and depreciation entries, and submit the same to the Commission on Audit (COA) for evaluation;
c. Direct the MEO and MPDO to continuously expedite the retrieval and submission of required completion documents (e.g., Program of Works, Certificate of Completion, and other supporting documents) to the Municipal Accountant for proper project identification and timely reclassification of other completed projects still recorded under CIP;
d. Conduct regular reconciliation and monitoring among the MEO, MPDO, and MAccO to ensure accurate tracking of project status and costs, and to maintain updated and consistent records;
e. Ensure that complete project details (e.g., project ID, cost, location, completion date) are maintained in all offices concerned to facilitate reconciliation and improve accountability over infrastructure assets;
f. Resolve the noted cost variance of P1,241,614.59 between the MAccO and MPDO records through joint validation, and institutionalize measures to prevent future inconsistencies.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accounting to:
a. Reinstate the derecognized Construction in Progress until such time that sufficient documentation is obtained to justify their derecognition in compliance with IPSAS 17;
b. Secure and maintain proper documentation such as disposal reports, inspection reports, engineering assessments, or reclassification memos for any asset derecognition transactions;
c. Coordinate formally with the Municipal Engineering Office to assess and document the condition of the projects under the CIP accounts and determine the nature of works undertaken to enable proper recognition upon reversal, and ensure this evaluation is supported by written certification; and
d. Strengthen internal controls over asset management and accounting to ensure full compliance with the recognition and derecognition criteria under IPSAS.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Accountant to:
a. Coordinate closely with the Municipal Treasurer’s Office to resolve all reconciling items, particularly those involving unidentified and unaccounted deposits;
b. Immediately prepare and record the necessary adjusting journal entries to reflect the accurate balances in the books of accounts;
c. Establish procedures to monitor the nature of the fund transfers and direct deposits to LGU bank accounts; and
d. Strictly comply with Sections 3.2 and 3.3 of COA Circular No. 96-011 to avoid recurrence and ensure fair presentation of financial information.

Recommendation/s:
We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to:
a. Secure an unequivocal approval (or disapproval) from the DILG Regional Director for foreign travel of the officials and employees to Korea and USA, referencing DILG MC No. 2022-147 as the basis for the Regional Director’s duty to act on the LGU’s requests and submit the same to the Office of the Auditor;
b. Submit the enumerated lacking documents, as discussed above and shown in Annex I-2 to I-6, otherwise, justify the lack thereof;
c. Submit a justification for the engagement of tour agencies in the two trips to Korea, including a comparative cost analysis demonstrating that the use of packaged tours was more economical or advantageous than claiming the Daily Subsistence Allowance (DSA);
d. Submit a justification on the inclusion of three (3) delegates who were not identified in the original letter request for travel authority addressed to the DILG;
e. Obtain a justification from the issuing agency as to the discrepancy between the duration of benchmarking (May 5–9, 2024) as stated in the certificate of participation and the actual travel dates based on available records (arrival on May 5 at 19:25 and departure on May 8 at 20:25);
f. Submit supporting documents such as the approved Daily Subsistence Allowance (DSA) rate and the applicable foreign exchange rate used in the computation of the daily allowance of ₱7,871.57;
g. Submit a justification on the seven (7) days exploration tour at various cities in various states in the USA, which were not part of the mission to be undertaken by the delegates based on the invitation letter and correspondence made to the host organization;
h. Submit a justification on the necessity of all foreign trips, the number of delegates and duration and why it should not be considered irregular, excessive and unnecessary expenditures, especially considering that, except for the travels to Singapore and Taiwan, the trips appeared to involve only minimal official visits to government or research institutions;
i. Require the concerned official to communicate with the League of Municipalities of the Philippines – Bukidnon Chapter and submit a detailed breakdown of expenses covered by the ₱200,000.00 registration fee paid, including receipts or equivalent documents, to establish the reasonableness, necessity, and allowability of the expenses in accordance with existing government accounting and auditing rules and regulations;
j. Require the concerned official to communicate with the Vice Mayors League of the Philippines and submit a detailed breakdown of expenses covered by the ₱160,000.00 registration fee paid, including receipts or equivalent documents, to establish the reasonableness, necessity, and allowability of the expenses in accordance with existing government accounting and auditing rules and regulations;
k. Official receipt or proof of payment for the airfare that reflects the final amount paid in pesos for the airfare amounting USD 4,169.80;
l. Submit a justification as to why the Certificate of Travel Completed were attached upon drawing of cash advance; and
Henceforth, ensure that a foreign travel authority is secured from the DILG and that supporting documents are complete in the grant of cash advance and liquidation thereof.

We recommended to the Municipal Accounting Office to:
Investigate the variance and determine the cause/s of such (e.g. errors in drawing JEVs and the like);
draw a Journal Entry Voucher adjusting the Due to PhilHealth account to its correct balance and furnish a copy to the Audit Team;
ensure remittances within the prescribed period for easier reconciliations; and
conduct regular reconciliations of records in coordination with the HRMO and MTO.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to: 

1.  Require the MEO to (1.a) copy furnish the MAO of the Summarized Inspection Report supported with individual Inspection Reports from the LGU authorized engineer(s) to serve the as the latter’s basis for recording of CIP and Accounts Payable;

2.  Require the MAO (2.a) to ensure that recording of Accounts Payable and JEVs pertaining thereto is supported with valid and complete documentation to ensure validity of the recorded transactions, (2.b) prepare appropriate adjusting entry taking into consideration the completeness of the required documentary requirements emanating from the MEO.

We recommended to the management to direct the Municipal Accounting Office to:
a.	make necessary adjustments, if any, to present fairly the financial statements at year-end and follow COA Circular 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015 in the recording of subsequent advance payments of RPT/SEF Tax;
b.	utilize the features of the accounting system used by the LGU (ECPAC) to ensure easier monitoring in the recording of advance payments for the current year and the years not falling under the latter

We recommended to the management to direct the following concerned officials:

The Municipal Treasurer’s Office to:
a.	expedite the updating of the Real Property Tax Account Registers/Taxpayers’ index cards (RPTAR/TIC); 
b.	hire and assign enough personnel to accommodate the same; prepare and submit the Certified List of Taxpayers to the Accountant to comply with Section 20 of the NGAS Manual;
c.	properly monitor those who paid in advance and subsequently removed their names from the RPT/SET receivable for the next calendar year


The Municipal Accounting Office to:
a.	base the RPT/SET Receivable set-up at the beginning of the year on the Certified List of Taxpayers;
b.	maintain subsidiary ledger for each taxpayer that will easily monitor tax collections and delinquencies

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor to: 

(1)  Require the MAO to (1.a) maintain Supplies Ledger Card for Inventories and reconcile the same with the GSD quarterly; (1.b) also, require the MAO to determine specific costformulas for each class of inventory and disclose the same in the notes to financial statements.

(2)  Require the GSD to (2.a) revise the SSMI form, (2.b) ensure that RIS’s issued attached thereof are in chronological order and (2.c) submit the same weekly to the MAO, and (2.d) expedite submission of the reports related to the issued inventory in CY 2023 and years prior, if any;

(3)  Require the Motorpool (3.a) to directly report monthly to the MAO using the appropriate form the overall fuel consumption for the month for each fund for appropriate recording, and (3b) expedite submission of the reports related to the issued inventory in CY 2023

(4)  Require the Motorpool to analyze the fuel consumption used by each fund and suggest that delivery of fuel be in accordance with the demand determined whilst maximizing the fuel tank capacity;
(5)  Require the GSD and the MAO to conduct   regular reconciliation of records.

We recommended to the management to direct the Municipal Accounting Office to:
a. 	facilitate provision of proper internal control in the recording of RPT/SET collections to proper accounts and funds;
b.	have periodic reconciliation of the reciprocal accounts;
c. 	make necessary adjustments, if any, to present fairly the financial statements

We recommended to management the following courses of action:
Set a timeline for the 
completion of the report required from the committee, which was organized to trace, gather and retrieve the documents of the unrecorded forty four (44) parcels of land to determine with certainty the mode of acquisition, whether through exchange (purchase) or through a non-exchange transaction;
If the land was purchased, determine its acquisition cost based on the gathered appropriate documents, such as the Deed of Sale;
If the land was acquired through non-exchange transaction (ex: donation or grant), the initial cost to be used shall be its fair value as at the date of acquisition.
With the committee’s 
verified report as reference, the Municipal Accountant shall make the necessary entries to record the costs of these lands in the books of the LGU, supported with appropriate documents;
Cause the immediate 
processing of documents for transfer, relative to the fourteen (14) donated properties, so that their recognition in the books of account can be made;
Present the Certificate 
of Titles (COTs) in the name of the LGU for the six (6) parcels of land totaling ₱16,112,108.67 as concrete confirmations of the LGU’s ownership. For those which have none, process and secure immediately their COTs in favor of the Municipality of Manolo Fortich;
Ensure regular 
reconciliation of the Municipal Accountant’s ledgers and the Municipal Assessor’s register of lands to assure that all properties owned by the LGU Manolo Fortich are duly accounted for and to guarantee that they are duly supported with the necessary documents in establishing their control and ownership.  The Municipal Accounting Office must also update their Land records (schedules and ledgers) to coincide them with the MAssO records particularly on the new Tax Declaration issued due to the General Revision made in CY 2018; and 
For subsequent 
acquisitions, ensure that the process of transferring the title in the name of the LGU will be immediately undertaken to avoid the occurrence of the same deficiencies.

We recommended that the following courses of action be undertaken by management:
a.	In the implementation of infrastructure projects, strict adherence shall be made to the approved Program of Works, and any Variation Orders and/or Extra Work Orders shall be properly documented and supported with necessary credentials to justify them;
b.	Submit justification and complete documentation on the material deviations of the actual equipment usage for the Closure of the Dumpsite vis-à-vis the programmed equipment utilization schedule; and
c.	Submit a Joint Inspection Report of the DENR EMB and the LGU showing 100% completion;

Recommendation:
We recommended to management the following courses of action:
Set a timeline for the completion of the report required from the committee, which was organized to trace, gather and retrieve the documents of the unrecorded forty four (44) parcels of land to determine with certainty the mode of acquisition, whether through exchange (purchase) or through a non-exchange transaction;
If the land was purchased, determine its acquisition cost based on the gathered appropriate documents, such as the Deed of Sale;
If the land was acquired through non-exchange transaction (ex: donation or grant), the initial cost to be used shall be its fair value as at the date of acquisition.
With the committee’s verified report as reference, the Municipal Accountant shall make the necessary entries to record the costs of these lands in the books of the LGU, supported with appropriate documents;
Cause the immediate processing of documents for transfer, relative to the fourteen (14) donated properties, so that their recognition in the books of account can be made;
Present the Certificate of Titles (COTs) in the name of the LGU for the six (6) parcels of land totaling ₱16,112,108.67 as concrete confirmations of the LGU’s ownership. For those which have none, process and secure immediately their COTs in favor of the Municipality of Manolo Fortich;
Ensure regular reconciliation of the Municipal Accountant’s ledgers and the Municipal Assessor’s register of lands to assure that all properties owned by the LGU Manolo Fortich are duly accounted for and to guarantee that they are duly supported with the necessary documents in establishing their control and ownership.  The Municipal Accounting Office must also update their Land records (schedules and ledgers) to coincide them with the MAssO records particularly on the new Tax Declaration issued due to the General Revision made in CY 2018; and
For subsequent acquisitions, ensure that the process of transferring the title in the name of the LGU will be immediately undertaken to avoid the occurrence of the same deficiencies.

Recommendation:
We recommended that the following courses of action be undertaken by management:
In the implementation of infrastructure projects, strict adherence shall be made to the approved Program of Works, and any Variation Orders and/or Extra Work Orders shall be properly documented and supported with necessary credentials to justify them;
Submit justification and complete documentation on the material deviations of the actual equipment usage for the Closure of the Dumpsite vis-à-vis the programmed equipment utilization schedule; and
Submit a Joint Inspection Report of the DENR EMB and the LGU showing 100% completion;
